            <pb facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Universal Diffusion of Life.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;Since the time<lb break="yes"/>when, in an earlier work, I attempted to
                    describe the<lb break="yes"/>universal diffusion of organic life on the surface
                    of the<lb break="yes"/>globe, and its distribution in height and depth, our<lb
                        break="yes"/>knowledge has been wonderfully augmented by Ehren-<lb
                        break="no"/>berg&#x2019;s brilliant discoveries, which rest not on
                        ingenious<lb break="yes"/>combinations and inferences, but on direct and
                        exact<lb break="yes"/>observation. By these discoveries the sphere of
                        ani-<lb break="no"/>mated existence&#x2014;we may say, the horizon of
                        life&#x2014;has<lb break="yes"/>expanded before our view. Not only is there
                    no inter-<lb break="no"/>ruption of minute microscopic forms of animal life
                        in<lb break="yes"/>the vicinity of either pole, where larger animals
                        cannot<lb break="yes"/>maintain themselves, but we find among the micros-<lb
                        break="no"/>copic animals of the South Polar Seas, collected in the<lb
                        break="yes"/>Antarctic expedition of Capt. James Ross, a remarka-<lb
                        break="no"/>ble abundance of new forms, which are often of great<lb
                        break="yes"/>elegance. Even in the residuum obtained from<lb break="yes"
                    />melted ice, which floats in rounded fragments in<lb break="yes"/>latitude 78
                    deg. 10 min. S. there have been found<lb break="yes"/>above fifty species of
                    siliceous-shelled polygastrica, and<lb break="yes"/>even coscinodisc&#x00E6;
                    with green ovaries, which were,<lb break="yes"/>therefore, certainly living, and
                    able to resist the ex-<lb break="no"/>treme severity of the cold. It is not only
                    in particu-<lb break="no"/>lar localities, in inland waters, or in the vicinity
                        of<lb break="yes"/>coasts, that the ocean is thus thickly peopled with<lb
                        break="yes"/>living atoms invisible to the naked eye. Samples of<lb
                        break="yes"/>water taken up by Schayer in 57 deg. S. latitude, on<lb
                        break="yes"/>his return from Van Diemen&#x2019;s Island, as well as<lb
                        break="yes"/>those taken between the tropics in the middle of the<lb
                        break="yes"/>Atlantic, show that the ocean water, in its ordinary<lb
                        break="yes"/>condition, without any appearance of discolouration,<lb
                        break="yes"/>contains innumerable microscopic organisms, quite dis-<lb
                        break="no"/>tinct from the siliceous filaments of the genus
                        ch&#x00E6;toce-<lb break="no"/>ros, floating in a fragmentary state like the
                        osciliatoria<lb break="yes"/>of our fresh waters. Some polygastrica which
                        have<lb break="yes"/>been found mixed with sand and excrements of
                        penguins<lb break="yes"/>in the Cockburn Islands appear to be generally
                        dis-<lb break="no"/>tributed over the globe; other species belong to both<lb
                        break="yes"/>the Arctic and Antarctic Polar regions. Thus we see<lb
                        break="yes"/>that animal life reigns in the perpetual night of the<lb
                        break="yes"/>depths of the ocean; while on continents, vegetable<lb
                        break="yes"/>life, stimulated by the periodical action of the solar<lb
                        break="yes"/>rays, chiefly predominates. Not only are earth, air,<lb
                        break="yes"/>and water, filled with life, and that at the most dif-<lb
                        break="no"/>ferent temperature, but also the interior of the vari-<lb
                        break="no"/>ous parts of animal bodies, there are animalcula in the<lb
                        break="yes"/>blood of frogs and of salmon; according to Nordmann,<lb
                        break="yes"/>the fluids of the eyes of fishes are often filled with a<lb
                        break="yes"/>worm which lives by suction (diplostomum); and the<lb
                        break="yes"/>same naturalist has even discovered in the gills of the<lb
                        break="yes"/>bleak an extraordinary double animal (diploson para-<lb
                        break="no"/>doxon) having two heads and two caudal extremities<lb
                        break="yes"/>disposed in rectangular directions.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i"
                            >Humboldt&#x2019;s<lb break="yes"/>Cosmos.</hi>
                </p>
            </div>
